abstract: Ury’s books about a German girl were so beloved, readers clung to them through the upheaval of World War II and passed them on to their children. But few knew that the author had died at Auschwitz.
snippet: Ury’s books about a German girl were so beloved, readers clung to them through the upheaval of World War II and passed them on to their children. But few knew that the author had died at Auschwitz.
lead_paragraph: Overlooked is a series of obituaries about remarkable people whose deaths, beginning in 1851, went unreported in The Times.

abstract: Moises Velasquez-Manoff responds to people from the state who commented on the contradictory nature of race relations there.
snippet: Moises Velasquez-Manoff responds to people from the state who commented on the contradictory nature of race relations there.
lead_paragraph: In my essay “Want to Be Less Racist? Move to Hawaii,” I explore why race might be perceived differently in Hawaii from how it is on the mainland United States. The article grew out of my interest in the psychologist Kristin Pauker’s research, which suggests that kids in Hawaii see race as something much more fluid than kids on the mainland do and that this fluidity can rub off on people from the mainland who enroll in college there.

abstract: Retailers are fixated on a pervasive statistic that says 80 percent of women are buying the wrong bra. Why?
snippet: Retailers are fixated on a pervasive statistic that says 80 percent of women are buying the wrong bra. Why?
lead_paragraph: Walk into a Victoria’s Secret, and the hundreds of colorful, lacy options lining the walls and piled upon tables — bralette, demi-cup, wireless, racer back, sport, strapless — will swallow you. But before you grab a few bras to try on, you need to hedge your bets on what size you wear.

abstract: Ms. Cortese, who starred in over 50 films, was perhaps best known for her role as a fading, tippling movie diva in François Truffaut’s “Day for Night.”
snippet: Ms. Cortese, who starred in over 50 films, was perhaps best known for her role as a fading, tippling movie diva in François Truffaut’s “Day for Night.”
lead_paragraph: Valentina Cortese, an Italian film actress best known for her role as a fading, tippling movie diva in François Truffaut’s “Day for Night,” which earned her a 1975 Academy Award nomination and, remarkably, an apology from the winner, Ingrid Bergman, died on Wednesday in Milan. She was 96.

abstract: Mountains, culture, beach. You can have them all. So plot an escape from the city, and then return that night.
snippet: Mountains, culture, beach. You can have them all. So plot an escape from the city, and then return that night.
lead_paragraph: When it comes to day trips, the journey can matter as much as the arrival. One or two hours on a train provides the time to get lost in a summer book, have an unhurried conversation and moon over the passing scenery as everyday anxiety ebbs away. These eight regional getaways have recently been road-tested, no car required (well, maybe a Lyft here and there). On some, you can be home in time for dinner; others will stretch past midnight. Most of them call for stamina and good walking shoes, and all promise a break from the routine, a way to see what adventures lie beyond the five boroughs.

abstract: Even if Democrats win the White House and the Senate in 2020, effectively combating climate change might require the elimination of the Senate filibuster.

abstract: Through a mutual appreciation of wealth, women and years of occupying adjacent real estate in Palm Beach and on Page Six, the lives of the two men routinely intersected for decades.
snippet: Through a mutual appreciation of wealth, women and years of occupying adjacent real estate in Palm Beach and on Page Six, the lives of the two men routinely intersected for decades.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — It was supposed to be an exclusive party at Mar-a-Lago, Donald J. Trump’s members-only club in Palm Beach, Fla. But other than the two dozen or so women flown in to provide the entertainment, the only guests were Mr. Trump and Jeffrey Epstein.
